85
00:05:00.740 --> 00:05:03.920
Okay, perfect. Today, I have the pleasure of speaking to you about real-world

86
00:05:04.020 --> 00:05:07.740
analysis of non-small cell lung cancer variant level frequencies from liquid

87
00:05:07.780 --> 00:05:10.000
biopsy testing in diverse US populations.

88
00:05:10.860 --> 00:05:11.760
Here are my disclosures.

89
00:05:13.720 --> 00:05:17.640
Biodesx operates across diagnostic and development services with the intention of

90
00:05:17.680 --> 00:05:21.140
transforming patient care and improving outcomes through timely and accessible

91
00:05:21.220 --> 00:05:24.890
personalized diagnostics. In this talk, I will be reviewing consolidated

92
00:05:24.960 --> 00:05:28.860
data from our diagnostic services arm of the business, specifically IQ

93
00:05:28.900 --> 00:05:29.520
Lung Testing.

94
00:05:31.740 --> 00:05:35.020
Lung cancer is one of the most urgent public health challenges in the United States

95
00:05:35.030 --> 00:05:37.570
and touches nearly every community and demographic group.

96
00:05:38.120 --> 00:05:41.950
It is also the leading cause of cancer-related mortality in both the United States

97
00:05:41.980 --> 00:05:45.890
and worldwide. Despite steady improvements to early detection and

98
00:05:45.980 --> 00:05:49.940
treatment, more patients will still die from the disease in one year than colon,

99
00:05:50.020 --> 00:05:51.680
breast, and prostate cancers combined.

100
00:05:52.700 --> 00:05:55.950
And the uneven burden of lung cancer motivates the need for large real-world

101
00:05:56.040 --> 00:05:58.020
genomic data sets that reflect community care.

102
00:06:00.050 --> 00:06:03.888
There are two different primary subtypes of lung cancerThe first being small cell

103
00:06:03.948 --> 00:06:07.448
lung carcinoma, SCLC, which makes up about 13% of

104
00:06:07.468 --> 00:06:10.488
cases. The other is non-small cell lung carcinoma,

105
00:06:10.828 --> 00:06:14.788
NSCLC, which equates to about 77% of cases, will be the topic

106
00:06:14.808 --> 00:06:15.478
of today's talk.

107
00:06:16.368 --> 00:06:20.118
This study assess real-world data of critical biomarkers known to be associated

108
00:06:20.128 --> 00:06:24.048
with NSCLC, as identified from next-generation sequencing and droplet

109
00:06:24.088 --> 00:06:27.378
digital polymerase chain reaction testing in the community setting in the United

110
00:06:27.468 --> 00:06:27.758
States.

111
00:06:29.528 --> 00:06:33.188
Approximately 350,000 tests were analyzed to produce these variant level

112
00:06:33.248 --> 00:06:37.208
insights. The average patient age in our analysis was mid to

113
00:06:37.248 --> 00:06:41.208
late 60s, aligning with national diagnosis trends.

114
00:06:41.218 --> 00:06:44.928
This alignment suggests that our data set reflects real clinical utilization rather

115
00:06:44.948 --> 00:06:46.808
than trial selected populations.

116
00:06:47.428 --> 00:06:51.028
We see consistent test ordering trends throughout the late 60s to early 70s

117
00:06:51.148 --> 00:06:54.318
range, mirroring the true NSCLC diagnostic window.

118
00:06:54.888 --> 00:06:58.728
Another important insight to note here is not just the average tested age, but the

119
00:06:58.808 --> 00:07:01.578
breadth of age of representation from community practice.

120
00:07:02.168 --> 00:07:05.968
This is important because mutation prevalence may vary with age, particularly

121
00:07:05.988 --> 00:07:09.628
EGFR enrichment in older never smokers and KRAS in younger

122
00:07:09.708 --> 00:07:10.188
smokers.

123
00:07:11.028 --> 00:07:14.988
Importantly, this data set also includes 20 self-reported ethnicity groups,

124
00:07:15.828 --> 00:07:18.928
shown to the right, which gives us visibility into testing patterns beyond

125
00:07:18.968 --> 00:07:20.908
traditionally well-represented populations.

126
00:07:21.628 --> 00:07:25.408
Ethnicity is an important demographic variable in lung cancer because

127
00:07:25.448 --> 00:07:28.768
mutation prevalence, access to testing, and outcomes are not evenly

128
00:07:28.808 --> 00:07:32.488
distributed. This is exactly why variant level real-world data are so

129
00:07:32.508 --> 00:07:35.548
valuable. They allow us to ask these questions at a population scale.

130
00:07:37.648 --> 00:07:39.728
To get into the demographics of our population,

131
00:07:40.528 --> 00:07:42.968
sex is another important stratifier in NSCLC.

132
00:07:43.568 --> 00:07:47.468
Biological men still have higher overall incidence in mortality, but younger women

133
00:07:47.548 --> 00:07:51.368
show increasing incidence, and studies have shown that actionable mutations occur

134
00:07:51.428 --> 00:07:55.228
more frequently in women. Our Genostrat DDPCR target panel data

135
00:07:55.328 --> 00:07:56.448
recapitulate this pattern.

136
00:07:57.348 --> 00:08:01.058
The approximately 20% of lung cancer cases occurring in non-smoker will also

137
00:08:01.128 --> 00:08:04.908
disproportionately affect women, reinforcing the case for reflex molecular

138
00:08:04.988 --> 00:08:07.068
testing regardless of smoking history.

139
00:08:07.908 --> 00:08:11.248
These findings reinforce that demographics are not just descriptive, they actually

140
00:08:11.288 --> 00:08:12.707
predict molecular actionability.

141
00:08:16.968 --> 00:08:20.348
Tissue genotyping as the gold standard diagnostic approach has known

142
00:08:20.368 --> 00:08:23.668
limitations like inaccessibility of tumor lesions for biopsy,

143
00:08:24.168 --> 00:08:28.048
minimal tissue quantity availability, invasiveness and infection risk,

144
00:08:28.468 --> 00:08:31.928
as well as patient stress associated with collection procedures.

145
00:08:32.548 --> 00:08:36.308
On the other hand, liquid biopsy profiling offers unique advantages like near

146
00:08:36.348 --> 00:08:39.869
real-time status monitoring, significantly faster turnaround times,

147
00:08:40.389 --> 00:08:44.348
non-invasive collection, as well as the ability to diagnose disease by capturing

148
00:08:44.368 --> 00:08:46.288
mutations from heterogeneous tumors.

149
00:08:49.228 --> 00:08:52.688
The Genostrat DDPCR test is a liquid biopsy-based, targeted

150
00:08:52.788 --> 00:08:56.248
qualitative LDT that identifies actionable mutations in

151
00:08:56.348 --> 00:09:00.088
NSCLC patients. It's highly sensitive and specific and targeted to

152
00:09:00.128 --> 00:09:03.388
clinically actionable mutations in EGFR, ALK,

153
00:09:03.838 --> 00:09:07.828
KRAS, BRAF, ROS1, and RET genes. The average

154
00:09:07.868 --> 00:09:11.748
turnaround time for this test is 2.6 days from lab receipt to test result

155
00:09:11.768 --> 00:09:13.268
delivery, making it ultra-fast.

156
00:09:15.588 --> 00:09:19.088
On the other hand, our NGS test is another liquid biopsy-based qualitative

157
00:09:19.148 --> 00:09:21.708
LDT, but covers a broad 52-gene

158
00:09:21.768 --> 00:09:25.608
panel. This provides an actionable, comprehensive report

159
00:09:25.668 --> 00:09:29.388
of genetic variations and associated approved therapeutics, which are all essential

160
00:09:29.448 --> 00:09:32.568
for the safe and effective use of corresponding products.

161
00:09:32.588 --> 00:09:35.598
And the average analytical turnaround time for this test is three to four days,

162
00:09:36.048 --> 00:09:37.288
balancing depth with speed.

163
00:09:40.348 --> 00:09:43.488
Robust standardized data management workflows are critical for integrating

164
00:09:43.548 --> 00:09:47.468
high-quality outputs across multiple assay platforms, as seen in DDPCR and

165
00:09:47.488 --> 00:09:48.358
NGS testing.

166
00:09:49.208 --> 00:09:53.128
Our quantitative variant level data from the QX200 and S5 systems

167
00:09:53.228 --> 00:09:57.128
undergo QC before being captured in the BioDustix LIMS, while

168
00:09:57.168 --> 00:09:59.928
qualitative data are recorded within Salesforce.

169
00:09:59.988 --> 00:10:03.848
The intentional separation between scientific data and customer-facing systems

170
00:10:04.228 --> 00:10:07.888
supports compliance, preserves analytical rigor, and enables secure

171
00:10:07.928 --> 00:10:11.028
multimodal data integration across multiple assay platforms.

172
00:10:11.668 --> 00:10:15.408
And the combination of DDPCR and NGS testing results provides a

173
00:10:15.488 --> 00:10:19.048
comprehensive landscape view of variant prevalence in non-small cell lung cancer

174
00:10:19.088 --> 00:10:22.768
over the past 10 years, from 2015 to 2025.

175
00:10:22.828 --> 00:10:26.228
Important to note, our data captures all disease stages, including metastatic,

176
00:10:26.288 --> 00:10:28.998
recurrent, refractory, as well as relapsing presentations.

177
00:10:31.008 --> 00:10:34.648
We analyzed 350,000 molecular tests across 20 self-reported

178
00:10:34.708 --> 00:10:35.548
ethnicity groups.

179
00:10:36.648 --> 00:10:40.088
All of our direct and indirect identifiers were removed prior to analysis, with

180
00:10:40.148 --> 00:10:42.048
geographic information being aggregated.

181
00:10:43.088 --> 00:10:46.308
Prevalence in this case is defined as the proportion of variant-positive results

182
00:10:46.448 --> 00:10:50.387
relative to total tests, with Genostrat DDPCR and NGS being evaluated

183
00:10:50.448 --> 00:10:50.908
separately.

184
00:10:53.288 --> 00:10:56.828
I'll now walk through the results by variant class, SNV, indels, fusions,

185
00:10:56.928 --> 00:10:59.168
CNVs, and DDPCR-specific findings.

186
00:10:59.708 --> 00:11:02.938
When comparing literature reported gene prevalence to our observed rates, it's

187
00:11:02.968 --> 00:11:06.228
important to recognize that many published estimates are derived from enriched

188
00:11:06.328 --> 00:11:08.168
academic or referral bias cohorts.

189
00:11:08.848 --> 00:11:12.688
In contrast, our data set reflects routine community testing across the US without

190
00:11:12.748 --> 00:11:16.668
referral bias. As a result, observed prevalences, while sometimes lower

191
00:11:16.728 --> 00:11:20.208
than literature reports, more accurately represent the molecular landscape

192
00:11:20.248 --> 00:11:22.388
encountered in real-world clinical practice.

193
00:11:24.628 --> 00:11:28.468
Beginning with SNVs, nearly half of our NGS tests returned at least

194
00:11:28.528 --> 00:11:32.388
one SNV, underscoring the molecular heterogeneity of NSCLC in

195
00:11:32.448 --> 00:11:33.048
routine care.

196
00:11:33.868 --> 00:11:36.508
Something important to note here is the broad national coverage.

197
00:11:37.168 --> 00:11:40.968
We see SNV positive results distributed across essentially all regions,

198
00:11:41.448 --> 00:11:45.308
reinforcing that actionable genomic alterations are not necessarily concentrated

199
00:11:45.318 --> 00:11:47.608
to a singular academic or coastal center.

200
00:11:48.668 --> 00:11:52.388
TP53 dominates as expected, and it's important to emphasize that

201
00:11:52.468 --> 00:11:56.168
most TP53 variants are not necessarily actionable, but

202
00:11:56.208 --> 00:11:59.368
instead reflect disease biology and aggressiveness.

203
00:11:59.428 --> 00:12:03.418
Internationally recognized HGVS nomenclature is used here to describe the variants,

204
00:12:03.848 --> 00:12:07.348
including P.? and P.=, which denote a protein

205
00:12:07.408 --> 00:12:11.368
impact is expected but cannot be reliably predicted,

206
00:12:11.708 --> 00:12:15.664
and that no change in the protein is expected, respectively.In contrast to

207
00:12:15.684 --> 00:12:18.904
TP53, KRAS G12C and EGFR

208
00:12:19.044 --> 00:12:22.734
L858R, while lower in overall prevalence, have immediate therapeutic

209
00:12:22.804 --> 00:12:23.584
implications.

210
00:12:24.504 --> 00:12:27.924
Variant level reporting allows us to distinguish targetable subtypes within the

211
00:12:27.984 --> 00:12:31.264
same gene, which would otherwise be obscured by gene-level summaries.

212
00:12:31.864 --> 00:12:35.804
Still, the observed prevalence at a gene level aligns well, particularly for

213
00:12:35.844 --> 00:12:39.504
TP53, validating the accuracy of liquid biopsy in real-world

214
00:12:39.584 --> 00:12:40.384
populations.

215
00:12:42.504 --> 00:12:45.924
On to fusions. Liquid biopsy is uniquely suited for fusion

216
00:12:45.944 --> 00:12:49.384
detection because it captures DNA shed from heterogeneous tumors,

217
00:12:49.784 --> 00:12:52.273
especially when tumor quantity is limited.

218
00:12:52.273 --> 00:12:55.784
This is particularly notable because fusion testing has historically been limited

219
00:12:55.804 --> 00:12:59.404
by tissue availability, while liquid biopsy enables detection even in

220
00:12:59.464 --> 00:13:01.844
geographically remote or resource-limited settings.

221
00:13:02.684 --> 00:13:05.624
CCDC6-RET was observed as the most prevalent

222
00:13:05.644 --> 00:13:09.054
fusion. We also see ROS1 and ALK fusions at

223
00:13:09.064 --> 00:13:11.514
expected but distinct variant level frequency.

224
00:13:12.504 --> 00:13:16.464
Despite their lower overall frequency, the fusion-positive map shows clear national

225
00:13:16.524 --> 00:13:20.384
dispersion, with RET, ROS1, and ALK fusions detected across multiple

226
00:13:20.464 --> 00:13:24.074
regions. These data reflect community-level fusion prevalence,

227
00:13:24.504 --> 00:13:27.324
not referral enrichment, which is often seen in academic cohorts.

228
00:13:28.464 --> 00:13:31.884
While fusions make up a smaller fraction of total tests, they represent some of the

229
00:13:31.924 --> 00:13:34.484
most clinically actionable alterations in NSCLC.

230
00:13:35.324 --> 00:13:38.504
The prominence of CCDC6-RET and CD74

231
00:13:38.524 --> 00:13:42.084
ROS1 highlights how fusion partners and not just the kinase matter.

232
00:13:43.104 --> 00:13:46.744
Importantly, we see multiple fusion isoforms within the same gene pairs,

233
00:13:47.164 --> 00:13:49.944
reinforcing why precise breakpoint annotation is essential.

234
00:13:50.644 --> 00:13:53.724
Variant level reporting matters here because different fusion breakpoints may

235
00:13:53.764 --> 00:13:55.524
affect therapy response.

236
00:13:58.204 --> 00:14:02.104
This map highlights copy number variation positive results, which are often

237
00:14:02.144 --> 00:14:06.084
underreported or missed entirely in tissue-based testing due to sampling bias.

238
00:14:06.604 --> 00:14:08.844
Liquid biopsy provides a global tumor snapshot.

239
00:14:09.484 --> 00:14:12.804
CNVs occur at a lower frequency than SNVs but carry high

240
00:14:12.884 --> 00:14:14.004
biological impact.

241
00:14:14.974 --> 00:14:18.574
MYC gain was the most common CNV, consistent with its role as a driver of

242
00:14:18.604 --> 00:14:20.294
proliferation and poor prognosis.

243
00:14:21.484 --> 00:14:25.384
We also observed gains in CCND1, FGFR1, and MET,

244
00:14:25.523 --> 00:14:27.304
which are all clinically relevant pathways.

245
00:14:28.264 --> 00:14:31.924
These findings demonstrate the value of including CNVs in routine liquid biopsy

246
00:14:31.984 --> 00:14:34.364
panels, even if prevalence appears modest.

247
00:14:35.364 --> 00:14:39.104
The geographic distributions suggest these alterations are a consistent component

248
00:14:39.164 --> 00:14:42.444
of NSCLC biology rather than region-specific phenomena.

249
00:14:45.824 --> 00:14:49.664
And this last map represents positive results from over 340,000

250
00:14:49.704 --> 00:14:53.504
individual ddPCR variant tests, giving us exceptional geographic

251
00:14:53.524 --> 00:14:55.153
resolution and statistical power.

252
00:14:56.044 --> 00:14:59.864
Across the 345,000 ddPCR tests, KRAS

253
00:14:59.904 --> 00:15:03.564
G12C was the single most frequent variant, highly relevant given

254
00:15:03.584 --> 00:15:06.404
expanding inhibitor availability.

255
00:15:06.464 --> 00:15:10.364
EGFR exon 19 deletions in L858R also remain prominent.

256
00:15:11.164 --> 00:15:14.864
ddPCR excels at rapid sensitive detection of known actionable variants,

257
00:15:15.084 --> 00:15:16.734
complementing NGS's broad approach.

258
00:15:17.464 --> 00:15:20.844
And this ultra-sensitive detection is reflected in robust

259
00:15:20.984 --> 00:15:24.764
KRAS and EGFR prevalence. Together with the NGS maps,

260
00:15:25.104 --> 00:15:28.674
this demonstrates how complementary technologies capture both breadth and depth of

261
00:15:28.764 --> 00:15:32.044
NSCLC genomics across US diverse populations.

262
00:15:35.004 --> 00:15:38.464
To conclude, this study provides variant level insights using one of the largest

263
00:15:38.564 --> 00:15:41.884
real-world NSCLC liquid biopsy data sets to date.

264
00:15:42.424 --> 00:15:46.264
Variant level data offers higher clinical resolution than gene-level summaries.

265
00:15:47.044 --> 00:15:50.364
Results highlight the importance of rapid centralized molecular testing, especially

266
00:15:50.404 --> 00:15:54.164
in underserved populations, and our future work will focus on deepening

267
00:15:54.224 --> 00:15:57.104
demographic resolution as the sample size continues to grow.

