clinical sequencing data.

1692
01:37:20.906 --> 01:37:24.646
Good afternoon, everyone. So I'll be talking about telomere maintenance in

1693
01:37:24.726 --> 01:37:28.566
cancer, and this work was co-led by me and Bill Diplas

1694
01:37:28.666 --> 01:37:31.586
in the Sphere and Morris Labs at Memorial Sloan Kettering.

1695
01:37:32.686 --> 01:37:36.606
And so some introduction. So in normal cells, telomeres shorten

1696
01:37:36.626 --> 01:37:40.426
progressively when the cells divide, and as a result of that, eventually

1697
01:37:40.506 --> 01:37:43.346
these cells reach a limit on how far they can divide.

1698
01:37:43.926 --> 01:37:47.846
However, cancer cells proliferate indefinitely, and to do

1699
01:37:47.866 --> 01:37:51.346
this, they have to maintain their telomeres as they divide, and this is a

1700
01:37:51.426 --> 01:37:53.606
universal hallmark of cancer cells.

1701
01:37:54.726 --> 01:37:58.266
So how do cancer cells do this? Well, around 85% to

1702
01:37:58.326 --> 01:38:02.006
90% of tumors do this by reactivating telomerase,

1703
01:38:02.466 --> 01:38:06.426
and these tumors are marked by, for example, TERT promoter mutations and

1704
01:38:06.506 --> 01:38:10.254
gene amplifications.However, a small subset of

1705
01:38:10.294 --> 01:38:14.054
around 10% to 15% of tumors do this by a

1706
01:38:14.134 --> 01:38:17.374
second pathway known as the alternative lengthening of telomeres, or

1707
01:38:17.474 --> 01:38:20.114
ALT, and this will be the focus of my talk today.

1708
01:38:20.584 --> 01:38:24.393
And this pathway is usually exclusive with telomerase base

1709
01:38:24.434 --> 01:38:27.994
reactivation and is marked by truncating mutations in ATRX and

1710
01:38:28.134 --> 01:38:28.454
DAX.

1711
01:38:30.074 --> 01:38:33.934
And so despite being rarer, ALT is highly clinically relevant,

1712
01:38:34.234 --> 01:38:37.914
and this is because it has high prevalence in several aggressive cancer types.

1713
01:38:38.974 --> 01:38:42.474
It also shows distinct clinical prognosis, seen here, for example, in

1714
01:38:42.554 --> 01:38:44.394
pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors.

1715
01:38:44.854 --> 01:38:48.794
And it has several targetable vulnerabilities that are under study

1716
01:38:48.874 --> 01:38:52.114
for targeting these ALT-positive tumors.

1717
01:38:52.954 --> 01:38:56.854
And so despite this, and despite interest in this pathway, it

1718
01:38:56.914 --> 01:39:00.354
has been challenging to use it clinically, and the reasons for

1719
01:39:00.594 --> 01:39:04.374
that are that the canonical marker, which is ATRX or DAX loss,

1720
01:39:04.474 --> 01:39:06.914
is neither necessary or sufficient for ALT.

1721
01:39:07.994 --> 01:39:11.594
Also, detecting ALT requires specialized non-clinical assays.

1722
01:39:12.394 --> 01:39:15.834
And prognostic effects of ALT are tumor type specific and hard to

1723
01:39:15.894 --> 01:39:16.574
generalize.

1724
01:39:17.614 --> 01:39:21.234
And so we thought that enabling large-scale detection

1725
01:39:21.274 --> 01:39:25.114
of ALT in real world clinical cohorts could solve this

1726
01:39:25.154 --> 01:39:28.214
problem by helping us identify novel genetic

1727
01:39:28.254 --> 01:39:32.104
drivers, enabling patient stratification for clinical analysis,

1728
01:39:32.454 --> 01:39:36.014
and also assessing prevalence and prognosis in several tumor types.

1729
01:39:37.334 --> 01:39:41.254
And so to do this, we turn to MSK-IMPACT, which is a platform that

1730
01:39:41.274 --> 01:39:45.214
has been routinely clinically sequencing patients at MSK for a panel

1731
01:39:45.254 --> 01:39:48.194
of 300 to 500 genes for over a decade now.

1732
01:39:48.854 --> 01:39:49.574
And thanks to

1733
01:39:50.454 --> 01:39:54.294
that amount of time, this clinical cohort is much larger than

1734
01:39:54.354 --> 01:39:57.714
any other cancer cohort used for such analysis.

1735
01:39:58.164 --> 01:40:01.974
And specifically for our case, it also has a lot of samples with

1736
01:40:02.014 --> 01:40:05.474
alterations in the key TMM genes that might be involved in telomere

1737
01:40:05.534 --> 01:40:06.114
maintenance.

1738
01:40:06.934 --> 01:40:10.694
And so we asked if we could use this cohort to study ALT,

1739
01:40:11.134 --> 01:40:12.354
and we began by

1740
01:40:13.174 --> 01:40:16.954
leveraging this assay that enables detection of biomarkers of this

1741
01:40:17.014 --> 01:40:20.754
pathway from patient DNA. And so we took this

1742
01:40:21.294 --> 01:40:25.014
assay and applied it to around 700 samples in the IMPACT

1743
01:40:25.074 --> 01:40:28.734
cohort. And shown here are the results of that with

1744
01:40:30.114 --> 01:40:32.814
the y-axis showing high ALT activity samples.

1745
01:40:33.274 --> 01:40:37.234
And so as you can see, ATRX and DAX truncations are consistently

1746
01:40:37.274 --> 01:40:40.334
associated with high activity in ALT.

1747
01:40:40.814 --> 01:40:44.694
But there is this population of tumors where this loss

1748
01:40:44.734 --> 01:40:48.374
is not needed for ALT activation, as well as this population of

1749
01:40:48.394 --> 01:40:52.314
truncated tumors that show no ALT activity in

1750
01:40:52.354 --> 01:40:52.874
this assay.

